<font color="#FF0000">NURSES</font><br>
<tt>Thu Feb  6 18:39:25 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Being a care-giver in a war zone is a race between insanity and numbness, for those that survived numbness was the usual winner.  The normal day consisted of waiting for the next batch of wounded while dealing with yesterday's batch.  Boredom could be a real part of any given time period, it could last an hour or a week.  Yet when the helicopters started coming in everyone went into instant high-gear, work was coming and you'd best be ready.  <br><br>
Along with that work would come the feelings knock-knocking at your door.  This required that you quick-like snatch off the switch that controls feelings; yeah this one will never walk again, that one's face will always scare children, and that poor fool is soon to be dead.  But, you can't allow yourself to feel.  Those were feelings that you couldn't get to feel, for to feel them took away your ability to help the next guy.  Afterwards we'll feel.  Yeah, maybe tonight, or next week at the very latest.  OK, it's been a couple of years now, maybe I'll get back to feeling things again.  Can't do that, because now it is for my own survival that I push the pictures, sounds and smells away.  Close to thirty years later and still so fast to turn on the switch in my brain that causes it all to go numb, no matter what 'it' is.  That is the legacy of VN for care-givers....  
